2026-04-16 12:19:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 6: input (+) terminal / internal series conductor'] hypothesis_explanation='Diagnostics show that up to Control Input Cable (+) 6 there is ~12 V, but from Control Output Cable 6 onward both conductors are at 0 V. Internal measurements inside module 6 reveal: (a) the input high terminal is at 11.989 V; (b) the switch node that should feed the output high terminal is at 0 V on both sides; (c) the output high terminal is at 0 V; and (d) continuity tests indicate that the input (+) cable’s port ‘n’ is floating/disconnected from the circuit, even though the cable itself has low resistance. This means that the internal trace/contact that should carry the high line from the input connector into the module circuitry (and then to the switch/output) is open. The missing green indicator LED is *not* the problem; the fault is an open circuit in the high series path at the input of Control module 6. Repairing/restoring the connection between Control module 6’s input (+) terminal and its internal high-line conductor (or replacing the connector/PCB carrying that junction) should re-establish 12 V downstream and allow the control LEDs and final lamp to operate when switches are ON.'
